          "body": "Christ does not merely make peace; *He Himself is our peace* (2:14). The cross accomplishes a double reconciliation in a single act. Horizontally, it breaks down the *mesotoichon tou phragmou* — the dividing wall of partition, the social-religious barrier that ran through the Jerusalem temple keeping Gentiles in the outer court on pain of death (Josephus, *Ant.* 15.417). Vertically, it puts to death the *echthra* between humanity and God by absorbing wrath in His body. The Law as a system of distinguishing ordinances (*dogmata*) is *abolished* (*katargēsas*) — not because it was bad, but because its dividing function has been fulfilled. Christ now stands as the new Adam, the *one new man* (*hena kainon anthropon*), and the church is humanity reconstituted in Him. The closing trinitarian formula of 2:18 caps it: through the Son, in the Spirit, to the Father — the most compressed Trinitarian access-statement in Paul."
